4 NEW SECTION. Section 2. Prohibition on access to child sexual abuse material. (1) A content
5 provider who produces, publishes, distributes, or maintains a substantial amount of sexually explicit visual
6 content in a manner in which the visual content is reasonably accessible in Montana may not produce, publish,
7 distribute, or maintain child sexual abuse material in a manner in which the material is reasonably accessible in
8 Montana.
9 (2) A content provider may not collect revenue or make a profit from distributing child sexual abuse
10 material to an individual a person physically located in Montana, regardless of whether the material is produced
11 or created by a third party or regardless of how the revenue is generated.
12 (3) A content provider who generates 50% or more of the content provider's income from the
13 production, publication, or distribution of sexually explicit visual content and who has generated at least
14 $500,000 in income may not produce, publish, distribute, or maintain child sexual abuse material in a manner in
15 which the material is reasonably accessible in Montana.
16 (3)(4) In an action filed under [section 3] alleging a violation of this section, it is a defense that a
17 content provider removes visual content that contains child sexual abuse material within 48 96 hours of the
18 visual content being made reasonably accessible in Montana.
19 (5) In an action filed under [section 3] alleging a violation of this section, it is a defense that the
20 person maintaining an action to seek remedies available under [section 4] caused the alleged violation of this
21 section to occur by uploading or otherwise causing the child sexual abuse material to be produced, published,
22 distributed, or maintained by the content provider.
23 (6) It is not a violation of this section to produce, publish, distribute, or maintain a hyperlink to a
24 third-party website if the hyperlink does not appear with visual content, regardless of whether the third-party
25 website contains child sexual abuse material.
26 (7) (a) Nothing in [sections 1 through 4] may be construed to place liability on a content provider
27 for reporting child sexual abuse material to law enforcement.
