4 NEW SECTION. Section 4. Remedies available -- apportionment of damages. (1) A plaintiff who
5 brings an action under [section 3] may seek any of the following:
6 (a) injunctive relief;
7 (b) declaratory relief;
8 (c) compensatory damages;
9 (d) punitive damages;
10 (e) statutory damages, which are the following amounts:
11 (i) $100,000 for a strict violation of [section 2];
12 (ii) $1,000,000 for a violation of [section 2] that is committed negligently or recklessly; or
13 (iii) no less than $5,000,000 for a violation of [section 2] that is committed purposely or knowingly;
14 and
15 (f) reasonable attorney fees and costs incurred in bringing the action.
16 (2) In addition to the remedies provided in subsection (1), a victim may seek restitution.
17 (3) For each unique violation under [section 2], a plaintiff's recovery of statutory damages is limited
18 to one subsection under subsection (1)(e)(i) through (1)(e)(iii).
19 (4) In an action in which the remedies under subsection (1) are ordered:
20 (a) compensatory damages for each violation must be paid to the victim; and
21 (b) the amount of punitive and statutory damages must be apportioned for each violation as
22 follows:
23 (i) in an action brought by a private plaintiff in which a victim is reasonably identified by the court,
24 regardless of the victim's involvement as a plaintiff:
25 (A) 50% to a victim, or equally divided among multiple victims, if reasonably identified by the court
26 regardless of the victim's involvement as a plaintiff;
27 (ii)(B) 30% 35% to a private plaintiff or, if there is no private plaintiff, to a victim, or equally divided
28 among multiple victims, if reasonably identified by the court regardless of the victim's involvement as a plaintiff;
